title: Atlassian co-founder Mike Cannon-Brookes asking $9 million for city home
text:
Cannon-Brookes is saying goodbye to his former landmark mansion in Paddington. The co-chief of Atlassian paid $7.3 million for the Hargrave Street landmark in 2010.
Since that time the Cannon-Brookes has had three kids and moved the family to Centennial Park where he paid $12 million in March for the Federation mansion Braelin .
​That property was formerly owned by car dealer Ian Pagent.
Collier is expected to launch the Paddington property next week for about $9 million after this weekend's sneak peek for his database.
Mike Cannon-Brookes has already bought – for $12 million – in Centennial Park. James Alcock At that level it is expected to easily top the suburb high of $7.75 million set in 2006 by a double terrace on Union Street, and matched in 2010 when developer Stephen Dunkley sold his renovated home on Goodhope Street.
